webpackJsonp([91914196067681],{1408:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Psyked.co.uk",author:"James Ford"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/James/Repositories/portfolio-2018/src/posts/targeting-multiple-browsers-with-css-and-some-javascript-trickery/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>There\'s a clever little javascript library that allows you to write CSS specifically for Chrome, the iPhone, IE 8, etc. all in a single file.  What it does is manipulate the HTML document client-side to add additional classes to the page, based on your browser type.  The end result is that your page gets additional selectors like .ie or .gecko added - and you can setup a single CSS file to target all of these browsers in one shot - no server side magic or conditional comments in the HTML.</p>\n<p>You can find more information here ( <a href="http://snipplr.com/view/9340/css-browser-selector/">http://snipplr.com/view/9340/css-browser-selector/</a> ) or download it from here (<a href="http://github.com/rafaelp/css_browser_selector">http://github.com/rafaelp/css_browser_selector</a> ).</p>',frontmatter:{title:"Targeting multiple browsers with CSS... and some Javascript trickery.",date:"November 28, 2009",tags:["css","javascript"]}}},pathContext:{}}}});
